		<td><b>Re: Is Kickstarter always a good idea?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Another thing to consider:<br /><br />kickstarter is one of many vendors/avenues of sale. You may consider and then audit your game to others: retroUSB, khan games, megacat games, infiniteNESlives, or as many do, simply put a buy thread up on NintendoAge once the software part is finished. <br /><br />If you perform a personal little SWOT analysis on these potential partners/channels, you'll probably get a satisfying answer. Of course, the game needs to be sufficiently developed for some of these vendors to be able to make a fair judgement if it's going to be just right for their webshop. <br /><br /><br /><br />One last thing on my mind regarding KS. One thing i see repeated often is the sentiment &quot;don't launch a project before you've backed a couple of project of similar nature and scope&quot;. It makes twofold sense to me: It'd put me in the position of the typical backer of my project, which i can draw useful cues from, and it's good for credibility. The credibility economy on KS is a bit fragile, since anything goes. The indie board game scene had a boom and bust similar to the atari market collapse some years ago. Since then, backers have become wary of a multitude of &quot;red flags&quot;, including first-time campaign creators who haven't backed anything prior.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


